The paper deals with data structures and algorithms for string processing, which is a topic that falls under the category of theoretical computer science. Specifically, the paper focuses on the problem of Longest Common Extension (LCE) queries, which is a fundamental sub-routine in several string-processing algorithms. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). 

The paper also presents a new data structure that supports LCE queries in logarithmic time and can be built in linear space. This suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of cs.CC (Computational Complexity), which deals with the study of the inherent difficulty of computational problems. 

Moreover, the paper provides efficient in-place algorithms for computing the LCP array and suffix-sorting, which are problems that are related to data mining and information retrieval. This suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-categories of cs.DM (Data Mining) and cs.IT (Information Retrieval). 

Finally, the paper uses probabilistic analysis to analyze the expected running time of the algorithms, which suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning).
